<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-266-964  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 266 964.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer  March 1990 v23 n3 p82(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Ruling clarifies US software-import rules. (the US CommerceDepartment's software-import policy)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gruman, Galen.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Commerce Department decides that the Singapore governmentsubsidized a computer-aided software engineering (CASE) systemimported into the US and may be forced to pay duties on futureimports of the product.andP;  Packaged software is categorized asmerchandise rather than as intellectual property by the ruling,which makes it subject to US countervailing duty law, according toa Commerce department official.andP;  Countervailing duties are taxeslevied against imports considered by the US to be unfairlysubsidized.andP;  US CASE manufacturer Visible Systems alleged inSeptember, 1989 that Singapore's National Computer Boardsubsidized the Picture-Oriented Software Engineering (POSE)analysis and design tool, which lowered its US price artificially.andO;The board developed POSE and contracted with Computer SystemsAdvisors to sell it abroad.andP;  Packaged software will now beconsidered the same as books and sound recordings by the CommerceDepartment.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Visible Systems Corp. (cases).andO;Topic:     Software DesignComputer-Aided Software EngineeringImportGovernment RegulationNational GovernmentGovernment AgencyTaxSoftware PackagesSingaporeUnited States. Department of CommerceSingapore. National Computer Board.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>